# Cursor Memory Bank — Read Protocol

My memory resets between sessions. The Memory Bank is the single source of truth for project context. This rule governs **when and what to read**. Use the `/update-memory-bank` command to write.

## Memory Bank Location

All files live at `memory-bank/` in the project root:

```
memory-bank/
  projectbrief.md      <- foundation; project scope and goals
  productContext.md    <- why this project exists; user experience goals
  systemPatterns.md    <- architecture, design patterns, component relationships
  techContext.md       <- tech stack, constraints, dependencies
  activeContext.md     <- current focus, recent changes, next steps
  progress.md          <- what works, what's left, known issues
```

## Selective Reading by Task Type

Do not read all files every time. Read only what is relevant to the current task:

| Task type | Files to read |
|---|---|
| Starting a new feature | `projectbrief.md`, `activeContext.md` |
| Planning or architecture | `projectbrief.md`, `systemPatterns.md`, `techContext.md` |
| Debugging or fixing | `techContext.md`, `progress.md`, `activeContext.md` |
| Unfamiliar codebase / new session | All files |
| Continuing from previous session | `activeContext.md`, `progress.md` |

## Core Workflow

### Plan Mode
1. Read the relevant files per the table above
2. If files are missing or incomplete, note it and ask the user before proceeding
3. Verify context, develop strategy, present approach

### Act Mode
1. Read `activeContext.md` and any task-relevant files
2. Execute the task
3. At session end, invoke `/update-memory-bank` to persist changes

## Triggering a Read

- The AI loads this rule when it detects a new task, planning request, or unfamiliar context
- You can also explicitly trigger it with `@memory-bank` or `/read-memory-bank`
